             sworn. - I am an <rs id="t18021027-6-viclabel35" type="occupation">oilman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18021027-6-victim94 t18021027-6-viclabel35"></join>: On Saturday, the 2dof October, about a quarter after one in the afternoon, passing along <placeName id="t18021027-6-crimeloc36">Lower Thames-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18021027-6-crimeloc36" type="placeName" value="Lower Thames-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18021027-6-crimeloc36" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18021027-6-off33 t18021027-6-crimeloc36"></join>, I had my pocket picked of a silk handkerchief; I turned round and saw the prisoner and a man in sailor's cloaths, the only two men near me; they sprang into the middle of the road, and I after them; when I was within about a yard of them the man who was with the prisoner passed my handkerchief into the hands of the prisoner at the bar, from whose hands I took it, and afterwards carried him to the Compter, the other man got away.(
               <persName id="t18021027-6-person95">
                  John 
                  Alderman
               <interp inst="t18021027-6-person95" type="surname" value="Alderman"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18021027-6-person95" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18021027-6-person95" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , a constable, produced the handkerchief, which was identified by the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's defence. I picked up the handkerchief on the spoke of a cart wheel; I don't know how it came there.</p>
               <p>GUILTY, aged 29.</p>
